Feature: the canonical lead CLAUDE.md primer directs the router to re-fire the product-discovery prompt each session until the product surface becomes non-empty, rather than firing the prompt once

  lead-vglj (P2) — product authority 2026-06-29: "for the lead to detect when the
  repo is effectively empty and start a product discovery conversation with the
  user to start determining the shape of the new system."

  This scenario pins the CADENCE half. SCOPE PINNED 2026-06-30 (product authority,
  David): the product-discovery prompt RE-FIRES each session while the
  effectively-empty / no-product-defined state still holds — it is an idempotent
  nudge, NOT a fire-once trigger. A first prompt that the authority dismisses gets
  another chance the next session. The router suppresses the prompt only once the
  product surface becomes non-empty — that is, once either signal of the
  two-signal detection test no longer holds.

  Split out of the proactive-initiation trigger scenario to keep one behavior per
  scenario: the trigger scenario pins "open discovery instead of idle"; this
  scenario pins "re-fire each session until non-empty".

  AUTHORING ONLY — no BC dispatch. @bc tag is the Architect's to apply at
  assignment time; @lead_integration:templates below is provisional placement
  matching sibling primer-furniture scenarios.

@lead_integration:templates
  @scenario_hash:c0bf83e11bb74f05
  Scenario: the canonical lead primer directs the router to re-fire the product-discovery prompt on each session while the effectively-empty state holds, and to suppress it only once the product surface is non-empty
    Given the "shop-templates" package ships a canonical "CLAUDE.md" primer template for shop type "lead" through its public template-access surface
    When I ask the package for that canonical primer body for shop type "lead"
    Then a non-empty template body is returned
    And the returned body contains a contiguous block directing the router to re-fire the product-discovery prompt on each session while the effectively-empty / no-product-defined state still holds
    And that block states the nudge is idempotent so that a previously dismissed prompt is re-issued the next session rather than fired only once
    And that block states the router suppresses the prompt only once the product surface becomes non-empty — that is, once either signal of the two-signal detection test no longer holds
